docs.abstract: Ms. Davis won best supporting actress for “Fences.” Mahershala Ali, Asghar Farhadi and Ezra Edelman provided other memorable moments.
docs.snippet: Ms. Davis won best supporting actress for “Fences.” Mahershala Ali, Asghar Farhadi and Ezra Edelman provided other memorable moments.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Oscars host Jimmy Kimmel joked that Viola Davis should get an Emmy for her acceptance speech upon winning best supporting actress for her performance in “Fences.” And it was a rousing speech, an ode to artists as well as a thank you to, among others, the playwright August Wilson, whose drama was the basis for the film, and her director, Denzel Washington. Here are edited excerpts from some of the evening’s acceptance speeches.

headline.main: Viola Davis and Other Speech Highlights at the Oscars

docs.lead_paragraph: As Black History Month commemorations start to wind down, one festival is just gearing up. Afropunk the Takeover — Harlem, running from Tuesday through Feb. 25, will celebrate black culture with music, art, film screenings, discussions and comedy.

docs.abstract: In many states, reducing the rate of incarceration has become a bipartisan goal.
docs.snippet: In many states, reducing the rate of incarceration has become a bipartisan goal.
docs.lead_paragraph: It promises to be a bleak four years for liberals, who will spend it trying — and, most likely, failing — to defend health care, women’s rights, climate change action and other good things. But on one serious problem, continued progress is not only possible, it’s probable. That is reducing incarceration.

headline.main: Even in Texas, Mass Imprisonment Is Going Out of Style

docs.abstract: Stephen Bannon and Jeff Sessions, the new attorney general, have long shared a vision for remaking America. Now the nation’s top law-enforcement agency can serve as a tool for enacting it.
docs.snippet: Stephen Bannon and Jeff Sessions, the new attorney general, have long shared a vision for remaking America. Now the nation’s top law-enforcement agency can serve as a tool for enacting it.
docs.lead_paragraph: One night in September 2014, when he was chief executive of Breitbart News, Stephen Bannon hosted cocktails and dinner at the Washington townhouse where he lived, a mansion near the Supreme Court that he liked to call the Breitbart Embassy. Beneath elaborate chandeliers and flanked by gold drapes and stately oil paintings, Jeff Sessions, then a senator from Alabama, sat next to the guest of honor: Nigel Farage, the insurgent British politician, who first met Sessions two years earlier when Bannon introduced them. Farage was building support for his right-wing party by complaining in the British press about “uncontrolled mass immigration.” Sessions, like other attendees, was celebrating the recent collapse in Congress of bipartisan immigration reform, which would have provided a path to citizenship for some undocumented people. At the dinner, Sessions told a writer for Vice, Reid Cherlin, that Bannon’s site was instrumental in defeating the measure. Sessions read Breitbart almost every day, he explained, because it was “putting out cutting-edge information.”
